The '''Canberra Centenary Column''' is a [[sculpture]] in [[City Hill, Canberra]], Australia. It was built to commemorate the city's centenary, and unveiled on 11 March 2014.<ref name="artsACT" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cmd.act.gov.au/open_government/inform/act_government_media_releases/gallagher/2014/canberras-first-100-years-sealed-in-centenary-time-capsule|title=Canberra's first 100 years sealed in centenary time capsule|date=2014-04-10|publisher=ACT Government|accessdate=2014-10-12}}</ref>

The sculpture is an {{convert|8.5|m|adj=on}} stainless steel [[obelisk]] on a {{convert|5|m||adj=mid|-wide}}<ref name="Q&A">{{cite web|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0BzCxhBE0EgTSUURxU3Q3R3NHLTNQcU8tNS1vazFyY2lVc2Zn|title=Questions and Answers about the Canberra Centenary Column and Time Capsule|date=2013-12-13|publisher=Canberra CBD Limited|author=Jane Easthope|accessdate=2014-10-12}}</ref> granite-dressed concrete base. The top of the base is inlaid with glass tiles and has a steel covering etched with images depicting Canberra's 100-year history.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.canberratimes.com.au/act-news/centenary-column--ticks-off-some-unfinished-business-for-canberra-20140311-34ja3.html|title=Centenary column ticks off some unfinished business for Canberra|date=2014-03-11|publisher=Fairfax Media|newspaper=The Canberra Times|author=David Ellery|accessdate=2014-10-12}}</ref> It was designed by local artist Geoff Farquhar-Still. The design was inspired by the "Commencement Column" that was proposed to have been built when Canberra was founded, but was never completed.<ref name="artsACT" />{{efn|The Commencement Column was to have been built on three foundation stones that were laid in 1913 to mark the founding of Canberra. The column was never constructed; the foundation stones have since been moved, and are included on the Commonwealth Heritage List.<ref>{{cite AHD|105347|Commencement Column Monument}}</ref>}}

Encased in the base is a [[time capsule]] containing one hundred objects,<ref name=ABC/> both symbolic and mundane.<ref name=CityNews>{{cite news|url=http://citynews.com.au/2014/time-capsule-burial-marks-centenarys-end/|title=Monumental end to Centenary|date=2014-03-11|newspaper=Canberra CityNews|author=Stephen Easton|accessdate=2014-10-12}}</ref> The time capsule is intended to be opened in 100 years,<ref name=ABC>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/local/stories/2014/03/11/3961082.htm|title=Time capsule sealed inside Canberra's new Centenary Column|date=2014-03-11|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|author=Louise Maher|accessdate=2014-10-12}}</ref> during Canberra's bicentenary.<ref>{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mWMlfXhNuvQ|publisher=YouTube|title=Launch of the Canberra Centenary Column|date=2014-03-11|time=2:20}}</ref> The [[ACT Heritage Library]] and the [[National Film and Sound Archive]] have catalogues of the capsule's contents, and copies of some of the items.<ref name=HeritageLibrary>{{cite web|url=http://www.library.act.gov.au/find/history/search/Manuscript_Collections/hmss-0375-canberra-centenary-time-capsule2|title=HMSS 0375 Canberra Centenary Time Capsule|date=2014-05-29|work=ACT Heritage Library Manuscript Collections|publisher=ACT Government|accessdate=2014-10-12}}</ref>

