'''Harvey Young''' ([[Ph.D.]]) is an [[African-American]] [[cultural historian]], [[theorist]], and scholar.
==Contributions== Harvey Young has made significant contributions in the fields of [[performance studies]] and [[critical race theory]]. He is an Associate Professor at [[Northwestern University]], where he holds appointments in [[African American Studies]], [[Theatre]], [[Performance Studies]], and Radio/Television/Film. A past President of the Black Theatre Association, Vice President of the Association for Theatre in Higher Education, and board member of the American Society for Theatre Research and the Yale Club of Chicago, he currently serves on the Board of Directors of the African American Arts Alliance of Chicago<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.africanamericanartsalliancechicago.org/bod.html |title=This website is for sale! - africanamericanartsalliancechicago Resources and Information |website=Africanamericanartsalliancechicago.org |date= |accessdate=2016-03-30}}</ref> and the editorial board of ''Theatre Topics''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.press.jhu.edu/journals/theatre_topics/editorial.html |title=The Johns Hopkins University Press &#124; Theatre Topics |website=Press.jhu.edu |date= |accessdate=2016-03-30}}</ref> He is Associate Editor of ''Theatre Survey.''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayMoreInfo?jid=TSY&type=eb |title=Theatre Survey - Journal Editorial Board - Cambridge Journals Online |website=Journals.cambridge.org |date= |accessdate=2016-03-30}}</ref>
==Books== Harvey young first book, ''Embodying Black Experience: Stillness, Critical Memory and the Black Body'' (2010)<ref>{{cite web|author=Harvey Young |url=http://press.umich.edu/titleDetailDesc.do?id=235634 |title=Embodying Black Experience |website=Press.umich.edu |date= |accessdate=2016-03-30}}</ref> chronicles a set of black experiences, or what he calls, "phenomenal blackness," that developed not only from the experience of abuse but also from a variety of performances of resistance that were devised to respond to the highly predictable and anticipated arrival of racial violence within a person's lifetime. The book won the Lilla A. Heston Award for Outstanding Scholarship and was hailed by ''Theatre Journal'' as "performance studies at its engaged and engaging best."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://muse.jhu.edu/journals/theatre_journal/v063/63.1.knowles.html |title=Project MUSE - Embodying Black Experience: Stillness, Critical Memory, and the Black Body (review) |doi=10.1353/tj.2011.0008 |website=Muse.jhu.edu |date= |accessdate=2016-03-30}}</ref>
His other books include: * ''Performance in the Borderlands'' (2011) with Ramon Rivera-Servera.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.palgrave.com/products/title.aspx?pid%3D328301 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=June 28, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121011201154/http://www.palgrave.com/products/title.aspx?pid=328301 |archivedate=October 11, 2012 }}</ref> * ''Re imagining A Raisin in the Sun: Four New Plays'' (2012) with Rebecca Ann Rugg, featuring plays by [[Bruce Norris (playwright)|Bruce Norris]], [[Branden Jacobs-Jenkins]], [[Robert O'Hara]], and Gloria Bond Clunie.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nupress.northwestern.edu/Title/tabid/68/ISBN/978-0-8101-2813-2/Default.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=January 10, 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109152758/http://www.nupress.northwestern.edu/Title/tabid/68/ISBN/978-0-8101-2813-2/Default.aspx |archivedate=November 9, 2012 }}</ref> * ''The Cambridge Companion to African American Theatre'' (2013).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cambridge.org/us/knowledge/isbn/item6878484/?site_locale=en_US |title=The Cambridge Companion to African American Theatre &#124; American Theatre &#124; Cambridge University Press |website=Cambridge.org |date=2015-05-27 |accessdate=2016-03-30}}</ref> * ''Theatre and Race'' (forthcoming, 2013). * ''Suzan-Lori Parks in Person: Interviews, Addresses and Commentaries'' (forthcoming 2013).<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.routledge.com/books/details/9780415624930/ |title=Suzan-Lori Parks in Person: Interviews and Commentaries (Paperback) |publisher=Routledge |date= |accessdate=2016-03-30}}</ref> * Black lives matter: Interviews, Addresses and Commentaries (forthcoming) 2017
