{{dablink|This article is about the dialect of American English.}}{{distinguish|Transatlantic accent}}
'''Mid-Atlantic American English''', '''Middle Atlantic American English''', or '''Delaware Valley English''' is a class of [[American English]], considered by ''[[The Atlas of North American English]]'' to be a single dialect,<ref>{{Harvp|Labov|Ash|Boberg|2006|p=236}}</ref> spoken in the southern [[Mid-Atlantic states]] of the [[United States]] (i.e. the [[Delaware Valley]], [[southeastern Pennsylvania]], [[South Jersey]], [[Delaware]], and [[Maryland]]). 

The dialect consists mainly of the widely studied subsets known as [[Philadelphia English]] and [[Baltimore English]].

This dialect of English centers most strongly around [[Philadelphia]] and [[Reading, Pennsylvania]]; [[Wilmington, Delaware]]; [[Baltimore, Maryland]]; and [[Atlantic City]] and [[Trenton, New Jersey]].<ref>{{Harvp|Labov|Ash|Boberg|2006|p=233}}</ref>



