{{Infobox WorldScouting | image2=2011 06 13 5654.JPG (5847644860).jpg | caption2= Teams gather | type = program | name = National Youth Leadership Training | image = National Youth Leadership Training.svg | f-date = 2003 |owner = [[Boy Scouts of America]] | country = [[United States]]}}

'''National Youth Leadership Training''', often called '''NYLT''', is the current youth leadership development training offered by the [[Boy Scouts of America]]. The program is conducted by [[Boy Scouts of America#Local councils|councils]] over five days for [[Boy Scouting (Boy Scouts of America)|Boy Scouts]], [[Varsity Scouting (Boy Scouts of America)|Varsity Scouts]] and [[Venturing (Boy Scouts of America)|Venturers]]. The Boy Scout and venture training programs merged in 2010. This training is a part of the national organization's [[Leadership training (Boy Scouts of America)|leadership training]] program.

{{TOC limit|3}}

==History==
[[File:2011 06 16 5452.JPG (5847481742).jpg|thumb|left|Participants set off on an excursion at [[Potawatomi Area Council#Camp Long Lake|Camp Long Lake]]]]

In 1949 Scouts from 24 councils in 16 states formed a Junior Leader Training Troop at [[Philmont Scout Ranch]] for a forty day training program in leadership and Scoutcraft. In 1950 the "Junior Leaders' Training Course was developed to give intensive training in Scouting skills and techniques to select Explorers. Each is trained with the end in view that he in turn will train other junior leaders. The course has four parts. The first is centered around studying leadership methods, organization, patrol method, Explorer crews, troop meetings, and camping skills. The second part deals with teaching the same skills. The third sees the trainees actually living the patrol method, using the Scouting skills. The fourth part is devoted to a model junior leaders’ conference, and projects in nature lore, special Scoutcraft skills, emergency service, and personal and group service.” In 1952 at Philmont Scout Ranch 270 participants and at Schiff Scout Reservation 436 participants completed junior leader training camps. At Schiff the program lasted for twelve days, a practice that continued until 1972.<ref>{{cite web|title=History|url=http://nylt-leadershipacademy.org/history/|website=NYLT Leadership Academy|accessdate=10 March 2017|date=2017}}</ref> In 1974 the Boy Scouts of America published the ''Troop Leadership Development Staff Guide''.<ref>Troop Leadership Development Staff Guide: {{Hanging indent |{{cite book | title=Troop Leader Development Staff Guide | publisher=Boy Scouts of America|location=North Brunswick, New Jersey | year=1974}}}} {{Hanging indent |{{cite web | title=Historical Background of Leadership Development:Troop Leader Development |location=New Brunswick, New Jersey| url=http://www.pinetreeweb.com/TLD-1974.htm|author=Lew Orans|date= April 12, 1997|accessdate=September 3, 2008 }}}}</ref> In 2009 the practice of adding names like Pine Tree and Golden Acorn to the program was supposed to end.<ref name="nyltguide2011">{{cite book|title= National Youth Leadership Training|publisher=Boy Scouts of America |location=Irving, Texas|year=2011|series=34490|isbn=978-0-8395-4490-6| url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/50223094/NYLT-2011-Syllabus| accessdate=Nov 1, 2011}}</ref> Some councils ignore that policy and use Grey Wolf, Top Gun National Youth Leadership Training, Golden Falcon NYLT, Timberline NYLT, and Brownsea NYLT.<ref>Grey Wolf at Northern Star Council: {{Hanging indent | {{cite web|title=Welcome to the Grey Wolf 2012|url=http://training.nsbsa.org/info/GreyWolf.aspx|publisher=Northern Star Council|accessdate=November 9, 2011}}}} Top Gun National Youth Leadership Training at Mecklenburg County Council: {{Hanging indent | {{cite web|title=National Youth Leadership Training Top Gun |url=http://sites.google.com/site/nylttopgun/home|publisher=Mecklenburg County Council|accessdate=November 9, 2011}}}} Golden Falcon NYLT at Transatlantic Council: {{Hanging indent | {{cite web|title=Golden Falcon|url=http://www.tac-bsa.org/GF.html|publisher=Transatlantic Council|accessdate=November 10, 2011}}}} Timberline NYLT at Utah National Parks Council: {{Hanging indent | {{cite web|title=Timberline NYLT|url=http://www.utahscouts.org/openrosters/ViewOrgPageLink.asp?LinkKey=21960&orgkey=2195|publisher=Utah National Parks Council|accessdate=November 10, 2011}}}} Brownsea NYLT at Northeast Illinois Council and San Francisco Bay Area Council: {{Hanging indent | {{cite web|title=Brownsea Staff|url=http://www.sfbac-nylt.org/PDF_files/WhyStaff.pdf|publisher=San Francisco Bay Area Council|accessdate=November 9, 2011}}}}</ref> In 2010 Boy Scout and Venturing youth leadership training merged so the language was modified to reflect participation by participants\.<ref name="adult">{{cite web|title=Adult|url=http://scouting.org/training/adult.aspx|publisher=Boy Scouts of America|location=Irving, Texas|accessdate=November 1, 2011}}</ref>

==Program==

Participants are organized in teams of no more than eight, exactly as a patrol in a troop.<ref name="isbn0839544901">{{cite book|title= National Youth Leadership Training|publisher=Boy Scouts of America |location=Irving, Texas|year=2005|series=34490A|isbn=0-8395-4490-1|url=http://www.bacarrowhead.org/training/NationalYouthLeadershipTraining.pdf|accessdate=Nov 5, 2009|nopp=true}}</ref>{{rp|page=Staff Guide-14}} A staff member, called a troop guide, is assigned to each patrol (a team) to coach, mentor, and present some sessions and activities, much as a den chief would in a den of a pack.<ref name="isbn0839544901" />{{rp|Day One-4}} During the training the senior patrol leader performs the same function for the training cohort as a senior patrol leader does for a troop: running meetings and events, delegating responsibilities, assisting Scoutmasters, modeling learning, displaying leadership, and recruiting participation.<ref name="isbn0839544901" />{{rp|page=Staff Guide-14}} In addition to generally assisting the senior patrol leader, the assistant senior patrol leader is expected to oversee audiovisual support, guide the service patrol, inspect campsites, and prepare a model campsite. Some participants find the combination of technology and outdoor education problematic. <ref>Technology and outdoors: {{Hanging indent |{{cite web|url=http://www.rvw-nylt.org-a.googlepages.com/description|title=Description of NYLT|accessdate=November 1, 2009}}}} {{Hanging indent |{{cite web| url = http://www.jltbsa.org/dcforum/DCForumID22/4.html| title = JLT and Woodbadge Observations| accessdate =July 30, 2008| date = July 3, 2002|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050110092307/http://www.jltbsa.org/dcforum/DCForumID22/4.html |archivedate=January 10, 2005}}}} {{Hanging indent |{{cite web| url = http://www.jltbsa.org/dcforum/DCForumID22/5.html| title = New JLT and new WB| accessdate =July 30, 2008| date = July 3, 2002|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050110092307/http://www.jltbsa.org/dcforum/DCForumID22/5.html |archivedate=January 10, 2005}}}}</ref> Administrative services and rule compliance are left to the adult supervision.<ref name="isbn0839544901" />{{rp|page=Staff Guide-14}} The training is presented either in a one-week format or can be split over two or three weekends. The program is often conducted at [[summer camp|resident camps]].<ref name="isbn0839544901" />{{rp|page=Staff Guide-15}}

[[File:2011 06 13 5624.JPG (5847056195).jpg|thumb|right|Participants use [[Dutch oven|Dutch ovens]]]]

The program includes patrol games and other activities used to teach event planning, communication, team development, teaching, leadership styles, setting goals, problem solving and other leadership skills. Patrols compete in lashing and a [[geocache]] game.<ref name=ripvan>{{cite web|title=Description of NYLT|url=https://sites.google.com/a/rvw-nylt.org/www/description|publisher=Rip Van Winkle Council|accessdate=November 10, 2011|date=August 3–9, 2008}}</ref> Creating a vision of success, setting goals, making plans, listening, problem solving, teaching, leading, and putting the needs of others first are all presented as important to effective leadership. The program provides opportunities to make difficult decisions using the tools of the [[Scout Promise#Boy Scouts of America|Scout Oath]] and [[Scout Law#United States|Law]].<ref name="The Youth Leadership Training Continuum: A Guide for Scout Leaders and Parents">{{cite web |url=http://www.scouting.org/scoutsource/BoyScouts/Resources/nylt.aspx |title=The Youth Leadership Training Continuum: A Guide for Scout Leaders and Parents |accessdate=January 5, 2008 |work=Supplemental Training Modules |publisher=Boy Scouts of America }}</ref> 

Program objectives include developing confidence, knowledge, leadership, teaching, motivation, team working, sharing ideas, sharing experiences, strengthening relationships between youth and adults, fellowship, and fun.<ref>Program objectives: {{Hanging indent | {{cite web |url=http://www.usscouts.org/usscouts/aboutbsa/vision.asp |title=BSA Vision Statement |work=U.S. Scouting Service Project |accessdate=July 22, 2008}}}}
{{Hanging indent | {{cite web |last=Great Trail Council, BSA |year=2011 |title =NYLT |publisher=Great Trail Council, BSA |url =http://www.gtcbsa.org/events/training/2011NYLTPacket.pdf |accessdate =October 13, 2011}}}}
{{Hanging indent | {{cite web |last=Pine Tree Council, BSA|year=2011 |title =National Youth Leadership Training|publisher=Pine Tree Council, BSA|url =http://www.pinetreebsa.org/training/nylt/welcome.htm|accessdate =October 13, 2011}}}}
{{Hanging indent | {{cite web |last=Aloha Council, BSA|year=2011 |title =NYLT|publisher=Aloha Council, BSA|url =http://alohacouncilbsa.org/Training/NYLT/|accessdate =October 13, 2011}}}}
{{Hanging indent | {{cite web |last=Blue Ridge Mountains Council|year=2007 |title =Foxfire (National Youth Leadership Training)|publisher=Blue Ridge Mountains Council|url =http://brmcreservation.org/camp-Foxfire(NationalYouthLeadershipTraining)_5.htm|accessdate =October 13, 2011}}}}
</ref> Many of the key course concepts are represented as [[mnemonics]] including planning and problem-solving tools that focus on what, how, when, and who; start, stop, and continue assessment tool; [[forming, storming, norming and performing|forming, storming, norming, performing]] often labeled the stages of team development; explain, demonstrate, guide, and enable or EDGE method; express, address, and resolve or EAR conflict resolution tool; right vs. wrong, right vs. right, and trivial ethical decision making; message, sender, and receiver communication; and reach out, organize, practice, and experience or ROPE approach to human value. <ref name="isbn0839544901" />{{rp|Staff Guide–3 }}

